.TH "TEMPORAL.DURATION.NANOSECONDS" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Duration.nanoseconds \- Temporal.Duration.prototype.nanoseconds
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]nanoseconds\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instances returns an integer representing
the number of nanoseconds in the duration.
.PP
Unless the duration is balanced, you cannot assume the range of this
value, but you can know its sign by checking the duration\(cqs
\f[CR]sign\f[R] property.
If it is balanced to a unit above nanoseconds, the
\f[CR]nanoseconds\f[R] absolute value will be between 0 and 999,
inclusive.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]nanoseconds\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
Use the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to create a new
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the desired new value.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using nanoseconds
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] d1 = Temporal.Duration.from({ microseconds: 1, nanoseconds: 500 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d2 = Temporal.Duration.from({ microseconds: \-1, nanoseconds: \-500 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d3 = Temporal.Duration.from({ microseconds: 1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d4 = Temporal.Duration.from({ nanoseconds: 1000 });

console.log(d1.nanoseconds); \f[I]// 500\f[R]
console.log(d2.nanoseconds); \f[I]// \-500\f[R]
console.log(d3.nanoseconds); \f[I]// 0\f[R]
console.log(d4.nanoseconds); \f[I]// 1000\f[R]

\f[I]// Balance d4\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] d4Balanced = d4.round({ largestUnit: \(dqmicroseconds\(dq });
console.log(d4Balanced.nanoseconds); \f[I]// 0\f[R]
console.log(d4Balanced.microseconds); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
.EE
